Title: AUCTIONS AND OPTIMIZATION: CLOSING THE GAP CAUSED BY DISCONTINUITIES IN DEMANDS  
Author: RINALDO A. JOSE, PATRICK T. HARKER, AND LYLE H. UNGAR Rinaldo A. Jose, Patrick T. Harker, Lyle H. Ungar, 
Keyword: augmented auction protocols; decentralized optimization; discontinuous demands; agent coordination  
Address: Philadelphia, PA 19104-6393,  Philadelphia, PA 19104-6366,  Philadelphia, PA 19104  
Affiliation: Dept. of Chemical Engineering, University of Pennsylvania,  Dept. of Operations Information Management, University of Pennsylvania,  Dept. of Computer and Information Sciences, University of Pennsylvania,  
Note: JEL classitcation: C61 The authors express their gratitude to the NSF (SBR 9708965) for partial support of this project.  
Abstract: Auctions and optimization are similar, but their diering assumptions and methods lead to dierencesor gapsin the types of problems they can solve. In particular, consider the case where agents with discontinuous demands are to be optimally coordinated. Optimization techniques can identify solutions but are unable to enforce them if agents are allowed to freely buy and sell goods. Auction-based techniques, on the other hand, can coordinate agents but require them to have continuous demand functions in order to converge. We illustrate the gap here by applying both the Dantzig-Wolfe optimization technique and the ttonnement auction procedure to a system of agents that solve linear programs (LP agents). We close this gap by detning an augmented ttonnement procedure which can both tnd and support system-wide solutions. We outline a formal proof that augmented ttonnement can do this for LP agents, and then we extend this proposition to systems of agents whose objectives are concave and whose feasible sets are compact and convex. 
